oad examines the interaction between Greek religion and the cultures of the eastern Mediterranean with which it came into contact. Robert Parker shows how Greek conventions for naming gods were extended and adapted and provides bold new insights into religious and psychological values across the Mediterranean. The result is a rich portrait of ancient polytheism as it was practiced over 600 years of history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aCivilization, Ancient. 0aCivilization, Classical. 0aGods, Greek. 0aPolytheism. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / Greece.2bisacsh  a3rd century.  aafghanistan.  aancient greece.  aancient polytheism.  aancient world.  abelief.  aeastern mediterranean.  aeuropean history.  afaith.  agreek gods.  agreek history.  agreek mythology.  agreek religion.  aindigenous people.  aindigenous populations.  aindigenous religion.  amediterranean.  anaming gods.  apolytheism.  apsychology.  aregional.  areligion.  areligious studies.  asettlers.  aspain.  athird century.  aworld history.  aworld religion.  aworship.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDTL Humanities 2020z978311073776908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831106675540 cprintz978052029394640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520967250423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520967250/original  a978-3-11-066755-4  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-073776-9  DTL Humanities 2020b2020  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles